{"title_page": "Neville Faulks", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder|name=Sir Neville Faulks|honorific_prefix=|office=[[High Court judge (England and Wales)|Justice of the High Court]]|image=File:Sir Neville Faulks.jpg|alma_mater=[[Sidney Sussex College, Cambridge]]|birth_place={{birth date|1908|1|27|df=yes}}|death_date={{death date and age|1985|10|13|1908|1|27|df=yes}}|birth_date=|death_place=|spouse=|children=3|termstart=10 January 1963|termend=31 December 1977|caption=Mr Justice Faulks in 1963 by [[Walter Bird (photographer)|Walter Bird]]|honorific_suffix=[[Member of the Order of the British Empire|MBE]], [[Territorial Decoration|TD]]}}'''Sir Neville Major Ginner Faulks''', [[Member of the Order of the British Empire|MBE]], [[Territorial Decoration|TD]] (27 January 1908 \u2013 13 October 1985) was an English barrister and [[High Court of Justice|High Court]] judge.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Sir Neville Faulks|last=|first=|date=17 October 1985|work=[[The Times]]|access-date=|publication-place=London}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nFaulks was the son of M. J. Faulks, and Ada Mabel Faulks; his brother Peter Ronald Faulks, [[Military Cross|MC]] was later a Circuit Judge, and was the father of author [[Sebastian Faulks]] and of barrister and minister [[Edward Faulks, Baron Faulks]].\n\nFaulks was educated at [[Uppingham School]] and [[Sidney Sussex College, Cambridge]]. He was called to the bar at the [[Inner Temple]] in 1930, at the early age of 22.<ref name=\":0\" /> On the outbreak of the Second World War he joined the [[Territorial Army (UK)|Territorial Army]] and saw action in North Africa, including at the [[Battle of El Alamein]]. He ended the war with the rank of [[Lieutenant colonel (United Kingdom)|lieutenant-colonel]], was appointed an MBE, and twice [[Mentioned in dispatches|mentioned in despatches]].\n\nHis legal career took off after the war. In 1946 he was appointed prosecuting counsel to the [[Board of Trade]], and developed a large practice in commercial and libel law. He was appointed [[Queen's Counsel]] in 1959. The same year he was appointed under the [[Companies Act 1948]] to investigate the affairs of H Jasper & Company Limited, a merchant bank which had failed; his report, released in 1961, led to changes in company law. He was [[Recorder (judge)|Recorder]] of [[Deal, Kent|Deal]] between 1957\u201359 and Recorder of [[Norwich]] between 1959\u201363. He was head of chambers at 1 Brick Court, a set which specialised in defamation law.\n\nIn 1963, Faulks was appointed to the [[High Court of Justice|High Court]] and was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]]. He was assigned to the [[Probate, Divorce and Admiralty Division]], which was later reformed as the [[High Court of Justice|Family Division]]. On the bench, some of his colourful remarks attracted controversy. Most notably, at a 1974 trial of a man who had kicked his wife, Faulks told him that \"If you had been a miner in South Wales, I might have overlooked it. But you are a cultured gentleman living in a respected part of the community.\" The following day, he admitted to having been \"an absolute ass\" and apologised in open court.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nFaulks retired in 1977. After his retirement, he published two volumes of memoirs: ''No Mitigating Circumstances'' (1977) and ''A Law Unto Myself'' (1978).\n\n== Family ==\nFaulks married Bridget Marigold Bodley (d. 1963) in 1940; they had two sons and a daughter. In 1967, Faulks remarried to Elizabeth Parham, widow of the Rt Rev [[Arthur Parham]], MC, [[Bishop of Reading]]. She died in 1982.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Faulks, Neville}}\n[[Category:British Army officers]]\n[[Category:1985 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Uppingham School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Sidney Sussex College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:English barristers]]\n[[Category:English Queen's Counsel]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Probate, Divorce and Admiralty Division judges]]\n[[Category:Family Division judges]]\n[[Category:English memoirists]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:1908 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Judge|name=Sir Neville Faulks|honorific_prefix=|office=[[High Court judge (England and Wales)|Justice of the High Court]]|image=File:Sir Neville Faulks.jpg|alma_mater=[[Sidney Sussex College, Cambridge]]|birth_place={{birth date|1908|1|27|df=yes}}|death_date={{death date and age|1985|10|13|1908|1|27|df=yes}}|birth_date=|death_place=|spouse=|children=3|termstart=10 January 1963|termend=31 December 1977|caption=Mr Justice Faulks in 1963 by [[Walter Bird (photographer)|Walter Bird]]|honorific_suffix=[[Member of the Order of the British Empire|MBE]], [[Territorial Decoration|TD]]}}'''Sir Neville Major Ginner Faulks''', [[Member of the Order of the British Empire|MBE]], [[Territorial Decoration|TD]] (27 January 1908 \u2013 13 October 1985) was an English barrister and [[High Court of Justice|High Court]] judge.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Sir Neville Faulks|last=|first=|date=17 October 1985|work=[[The Times]]|access-date=|publication-place=London}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nFaulks was the son of M. J. Faulks, and Ada Mabel Faulks; his brother Peter Ronald Faulks, [[Military Cross|MC]] was later a Circuit Judge, and was the father of author [[Sebastian Faulks]] and of barrister and minister [[Edward Faulks, Baron Faulks]].\n\nFaulks was educated at [[Uppingham School]] and [[Sidney Sussex College, Cambridge]]. He was called to the bar at the [[Inner Temple]] in 1930, at the early age of 22.<ref name=\":0\" /> On the outbreak of the Second World War he joined the [[Territorial Army (UK)|Territorial Army]] and saw action in North Africa, including at the [[Battle of El Alamein]]. He ended the war with the rank of [[Lieutenant colonel (United Kingdom)|lieutenant-colonel]], was appointed an MBE, and twice [[Mentioned in dispatches|mentioned in despatches]].\n\nHis legal career took off after the war. In 1946 he was appointed prosecuting counsel to the [[Board of Trade]], and developed a large practice in commercial and libel law. He was appointed [[Queen's Counsel]] in 1959. The same year he was appointed under the [[Companies Act 1948]] to investigate the affairs of H Jasper & Company Limited, a merchant bank which had failed; his report, released in 1961, led to changes in company law. He was [[Recorder (judge)|Recorder]] of [[Deal, Kent|Deal]] between 1957\u201359 and Recorder of [[Norwich]] between 1959\u201363. He was head of chambers at 1 Brick Court, a set which specialised in defamation law.\n\nIn 1963, Faulks was appointed to the [[High Court of Justice|High Court]] and was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]]. He was assigned to the [[Probate, Divorce and Admiralty Division]], which was later reformed as the [[High Court of Justice|Family Division]]. On the bench, some of his colourful remarks attracted controversy. Most notably, at a 1974 trial of a man who had kicked his wife, Faulks told him that \"If you had been a miner in South Wales, I might have overlooked it. But you are a cultured gentleman living in a respected part of the community.\" The following day, he admitted to having been \"an absolute ass\" and apologised in open court.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nFaulks retired in 1977. After his retirement, he published two volumes of memoirs: ''No Mitigating Circumstances'' (1977) and ''A Law Unto Myself'' (1978).\n\n== Family ==\nFaulks married Bridget Marigold Bodley (d. 1963) in 1940; they had two sons and a daughter. In 1967, Faulks remarried to Elizabeth Parham, widow of the Rt Rev [[Arthur Parham]], MC, [[Bishop of Reading]]. She died in 1982.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Faulks, Neville}}\n[[Category:British Army officers]]\n[[Category:1985 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Uppingham School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Sidney Sussex College, Cambridge]]\