lericay.essex.sch.uk |date= |accessdate=15 June 2009}}</ref> is an [[Academy (English school)|academy secondary school]] and [[sixth form]] college<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/sixth_form |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090727133819/http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/sixth_form |url-status = dead|archive-date=27 July 2009 |title=Sixth Form / The Billericay School - A Specialist Maths & Computer School |publisher=Billericay.essex.sch.uk |date= |accessdate=15 June 2009 }}</ref> located in [[Billericay]], England.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/contact_us |title=Contact Us / The Billericay School - A Specialist Maths & Computer School |publisher=Billericay.essex.sch.uk |date= |accessdate=15 June 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090728033641/http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/contact_us |archivedate=28 July 2009  }}</ref> The school is led by headmaster Ahson Mohammed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/about_us/headteacher |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712035122/http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/about_us/headteacher |url-status = dead|archive-date=12 July 2011 |title=Headteacher / About Us / The Billericay School - A Specialist Maths & Computer School |publisher=Billericay.essex.sch.uk |date= |accessdate=15 June 2009 }}</ref> and has an enrollment of 1695. As part of the [[Billericay Education Consortium]]  the school forms part of a grouping considered to provide the best teacher training in the country according to the ''Good Teacher Training Guide''.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-14486989 | work=BBC News | title=Billericay Consortium 'top' for teacher training | date=11 August 2011}}</ref> According to [[Ofsted]] the school is \"an over-subscribed Mathematics and Computing specialist school mainly serving the town of [[Billericay]] but also drawing students from [[Basildon]] and nearby areas\".<ref>Ofsted, The Billericay School, Inspection Report, 5 March 2008, p3.</ref> In its most recent Ofsted inspection in 2013, the school was graded as 'good'.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Ofsted {{!}} The Billericay School|url = http://reports.ofsted.gov.uk/inspection-reports/find-inspection-report/provider/ELS/136861|website = reports.ofsted.gov.uk|accessdate = 11 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Admissions==\nAs a comprehensive school admission is primarily dictated by residing in/proximity to the catchment area as well as the presence of siblings at the school. However, the school is able to operate some academic selection and 10% of applicants are chosen based on aptitude in ICT which is one of the school's specialisms.\n\nThe 2013 admissions document lists a number of criteria to determine priority in the event of over-subscription for places:\n*Relevant looked-after children as defined in Section 22 of the Children Act 1989\n*Children residing in the school\u2019s defined catchment area\n*Children with a sibling attending the school\n*Medical grounds, supported by a doctor\u2019s certificate.\n*Distance from the home to school (based on straight line measurement) with those living nearer being accorded the higher priority.\n\nFurther information relating to admissions can be found on the school's website.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/parents/admissions |accessdate=18 February 2016 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229133059/http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/parents/admissions |archivedate=29 February 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Academic reputation==\nThe 2012 Governor's report lists a number of academic achievements at [[GCSE]] and [[GCE Advanced Level|A-level]].<ref name=\"aboutus\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/about_us/governing_body/governing_body_reports |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130505154056/http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/about_us/governing_body/governing_body_reports |url-status = dead|archive-date=5 May 2013 |accessdate=28 April 2013 }}</ref>\n\n*84% of GCSE students at the school gained 5 A*-C grades in any subjects.<ref name=\"aboutus\" />\n*100% of GCSE  students gained a A*-C grade pass in ICT<ref name=\"aboutus\" />\n*78% of GCSE  students gained a A*-C grade pass in Mathematics<ref name=\"aboutus\" />\n*78* of GCSE  students gained at least 2 A*-C grade passes in Science<ref name=\"aboutus\" />\n*The mean average points total for a GCSE student was 452 which is equivalent to 10 GCSEs at grade 'B'.<ref name=\"aboutus\" />\n*At A-level the mean points total per student was 874.2 which is approximately equivalent to ABBb<ref name=\"aboutus\" />\n*47.2% of grades at A-level were either 'A' or 'B'<ref name=\"aboutus\" />\n*25 A* grades were achieved at A-level<ref name=\"aboutus\" />\n\n{| style=\"margin:1em auto 1em auto; width:40%;\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! '''League Table Measure''' !! '''2012'''  !! '''2013'''\n|-\n| 5 A*-C (inc English and Maths) || 57%<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.education.gov.uk/cgi-bin/schools/performance/school.pl?urn=136861 |title=The Department for Education - Performance Tables - School Details |publisher=Education.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref> ||73%<ref name=\"telegraph1\">{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/leaguetables/10590631/GCSE-school-league-tables-2014-compare-your-schools-performance.html#area/Essex/136861 | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first1=Joel | last1=Gunter | first2=Graeme | last2=Paton | first3=Dan | last3=Palmer | first4=Siva | last4=Bonagiri | first5=Mark | last5=Oliver | title=GCSE school league tables 2014: compare your school's performance | date=23 January 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| English Bacc %<ref>The percentage of students gaining 5 A*-C grades in Maths, English, two science subjects, a language and either history or geography</ref> || 6%<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/special/education/school_tables/secondary/12/html/va_881.stm?compare= | work=BBC News | title=Secondary school league tables in Essex | date=23 April 2013}}</ref> ||25%<ref name=\"telegraph1\"/>\n|-\n| Value Added<ref>A  measure of how well pupils are helped to progress from their starting point. A score above 1,000 is better than the national average</ref> || 996.5<ref name=\"bbc\" /> || \n|-\n| Average A/AS- level points || 874.7<ref name=\"bbc\" /> || \n|}\n\n2009/10 leavers data showed that 73% of A-level leavers go onto another educational destination, 70 students went on to higher education and  9 of these students went on to [[Russell Group]] universities.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/interactive/2012/jul/18/oxbridge-students-secondary-school | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Simon | last=Rogers | title=Higher education destination by school: find out how many students from your school go to Oxbridge and top universities? | date=18 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Head teachers==\n{| style=\"margin:1em auto 1em auto; width:40%;\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Head Teacher\n|-\n|1938\u20131949 ||Percy George White\n|-\n|1949\u20131955 ||Ronald Eden\n|-\n|1955\u20131968 ||John Goldwin\n|-\n|1968\u20131991 ||Arthur Lingard\n|-\n|1991\u20131998||Robert Goodier\n|-\n|1998<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = Long-serving Billericay headteacher to retire after 17 years at school|url = http://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/11831870.Long_serving_Billericay_headteacher_to_retire_after_17_years_at_school/?ref=mr|website = Echo|accessdate = 12 August 2015}}</ref>\u20132015<ref name=\":0\" />||Sue Hammond\n|-\n|2015\u2013Present||Ahxx Mohammed<ref>http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/assets/Uploads/Parents/Newsletters/Newsletter-Summer-July-2015.pdf</ref>\n|}\n\n==History==\nThe school was formally opened in 1938 by admiral Sir Vernon Haggard using a ceremonial silver key handed to him by the first headmaster P.G. White. However, a predecessor institution called Great Burstead Board School opened on 13 February  1878. This school was situated just across from Laindon Road and P.G. White who was Billericay School's first headmaster was appointed head of the senior mixed department here in 1923. The Billericay School was built as by the 1930s the school was struggling to cope with a growing enrollment and plans were drawn up for a new school big enough to cater for Billericay\u2019s growing population.\n\nCosting \u00a322,400 Billericay School opened its doors in 1937 a year before its 'official' opening as a [[grammar school]]. Air raid shelters were built almost immediately  to protect students from Luftwaffe planes travelling to London on bombing raids during World War II. The school was built upon the site of an Iron Age foundry where prior to the building of the school a cornfield and a farm was located.\n\nP.G. White served a headmaster until 1949 when he died suddenly on holiday shortly before he was due to retire. Arthur Lingard became headmaster in 1949 and oversaw the school's transformation to a comprehensive on 1 September 1968 and the building of the school\u2019s sixth form centre which occurred in the 1960s. During the 1970s exchanges began with international schools including an annual trip to the Einstein Gymnasium in [[Reutlingen]] in Germany - an exchange programme that continues to this day.  The Parents\u2019 Guild (later Friends of Billericay School) was also formed in this decade. Robert Goodier became headmaster in 1991 and oversaw the move away from LEA governance to self-governance.\n\nThe school's Music Studio was finished in 1991 and the decade saw a period of success for the Music Department under the headship of Mr John Stevenson (blatant nonce) including appearances at the London TV Arts Festival and on the BBC's Blue Peter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCvWxoBF-FHkUQ06lWN0ImLg?feature=watch |title=John Stevenson |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref> In 1997 the school was awarded its third Schools Curriculum Award by Princess Anne. Sue Hammond became the first female head of the school in Easter 1998 and in 1999 the [[Resource-based learning|Resource Based Learning Centre]] (RBLC) was opened. In March 2002 the school was the subject of a channel 5 documentary concerning a school reunion for pupils who attended the school between 1980 and 1982.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9Y-vAFei0og |title=Billericay School Reunion - March 2002 |publisher=YouTube |date=26 August 2012 |accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Billericayschool.jpg|thumb|right|300px|A-block can be seen in the background of the front cover of Sylvia Kent's book on The Billericay School.]]\n\nThe School achieved [[Mathematics and Computing College|Maths and Computing College]] status in 2003 allowing some use of selection based on aptitude in these subjects. It was thought that this status would generate an additional \u00a31 million worth of funding, but a [[government]] policy on foundation schools reduced this sum significantly. The school has since converted to academy status, but continues to have Maths and Computing as a specialism.\n\nThe 2000s saw long-running attempts to sell disused land adjacent to the school in order to fund a series of improvements\nDevelopment was initially refused<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basildonrecorder.co.uk/search/2072077.Billericay_School_plan_set_for_refusal/ |title=Billericay School plan set for refusal (From Basildon Recorder) |publisher=Basildonrecorder.co.uk |date=26 February 2008 |accessdate=15 June 2009}}</ref> but was appealed.<ref name=\"billericay3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/local_news/billericay/3982265.Planning_inquiry_told_green_belt_land_sale_vital_for_Billericay_School/ |title=Planning inquiry told green belt land sale vital for Billericay School (From Echo) |publisher=Echo-news.co.uk |date=17 December 2008 |accessdate=15 June 2009}}</ref> In 2009 approval was gained to develop 51 new homes upon a six-acre plot.<ref name=\"billericay3\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/local_news/billericay/4079551.Green_belt_homes_fury/ |title=Green belt homes fury (From Echo) |publisher=Echo-news.co.uk |date=28 January 2009 |accessdate=12 June 2009}}</ref><ref>http://www.investmentland.com/news.php</ref>\n\nChanges were made in the 2005/06 academic year which cut the lunch break from 1 hour to 45 mins so that the school day finished at 3.00pm rather than 3.15pm. In January 2007 the school was at scene of a [[BBC London]] news report after a gas explosion scare in nearby South Green, down Southend Road. The school was used to house those evacuated from the surrounding area. No explosion from the acetylene and oxygen cylinders occurred but one man suffered burns from the fire. The scare scene was 3 houses away from the South Green Memorial Hall.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/essex/6299355.stm | work=BBC News | title=Explosion fear prompts evacuation | date=25 January 2007 | accessdate=25 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 it was proposed that the a Billericay Community Trust be formed in order to increase standards at the school.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basildonrecorder.co.uk/search/1407975.Schools_welcome_the_chance_to_cut_loose/ |title=Schools welcome the chance to cut loose (From Basildon Recorder) |publisher=Basildonrecorder.co.uk |date=19 May 2007 |accessdate=15 June 2009}}</ref> This would involve a partnership with the multinational technology corporation [[Dell]], something that the Essex branch of the [[National Union of Teachers]] has objected to.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/content/download/623/2660/version/1/file/Billericay+Community+Trust+Statutory+Proposals.pdf |accessdate=18 February 2016 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120217065424/http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/content/download/623/2660/version/1/file/Billericay+Community+Trust+Statutory+Proposals.pdf |archivedate=17 February 2012 }}</ref>\nIn 2010 The School suffered from austerity measure budget cuts and was one of several schools in Essex which lost out on money promised under the [[Building Schools for the Future]] programme.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/8259630.Government_pulls_plug_on_project_to_refurbish_seven_south_Essex_schools/ |title=Government pulls plug on project to refurbish seven south Essex schools |publisher=Echo-news.co.uk |date=8 July 2010 |accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref>\n[[Image:Menenpoort ieper.jpg|thumb|left|The school stage an annual trip for GCSE History students to the see World War I battlefields in Belgium taking in sites including the [[Menin Gate]] (pictured).]]\n\nIn 2011 the school received media attention when a local newspaper called the [[Billericay Gazette]] printed indiscreet [[Twitter]] comments made by Charlotte Berry who was a Deputy Headteacher at the school. Responding to the incident headmistress Sue Hammond stated: \"The member of staff\u2019s Twitter account appears to have been individually targeted, accessing conversations with friends unconnected with the school and taken completely out of context. The school is saddened that the decision has been taken to print these individual unrelated comments, however indiscreet, in a newspaper medium to an audience for whom they were not intended\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2051255/Billericay-assistant-head-Charlotte-Berry-investigated-expletive-filled-Twitter-posts.html | location=London | work=Daily Mail | first=Emily | last=Allen | title='I'm a lazy slut and I swear a lot': Essex assistant headteacher, 42, sparks investigation for her 'talk to teens' Twitter posts | date=20 October 2011}}</ref> There was further controversy that year when the school's sixth-form prom ended after some students were allegedly found taking drugs.<ref>{{cite web |last=Gazette |first=Billericay |url=http://www.thisistotalessex.co.uk/Prom-night-ended-drugs/story-13026028-detail/story.html |title=Prom night ended after drugs found |publisher=Thisistotalessex.co.uk |date=30 July 2011 |accessdate=17 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131107034532/http://www.thisistotalessex.co.uk/Prom-night-ended-drugs/story-13026028-detail/story.html |archive-date=7 November 2013 |url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nThe school converted to academy status on 1 July 2011.<ref name=\"aboutus\" /> Becoming an academy school gives the school greater budgetary autonomy and control over its curriculum.In 2013 the school received national media attention after banning male students from having [[pompadour (hairstyle)|pompadour]] style haircuts. The measure was criticized as draconian by some parents. One parent told the Daily Mail newspaper: \"I can understand banning some extreme haircuts but this is just ridiculous. This haircut has been about since the 50s and it didn't even shock people then\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2333446/Essex-school-warns-pupils-banned-classroom-copying-TOWIE-haircuts.html | location=London | work=Daily Mail | title=Essex school warns pupils they will be banned from the classroom for copying TOWIE haircuts | first=Tara | last=Brady | date=30 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 the school announced a partnership to aid [[The Deanes School]] in Benfleet which has been threatened with closure due to falling student numbers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/11000275.Joining_with_Deanes_will_make_us_both_stronger/ |title=Joining with Deanes will make us both stronger |publisher=Echo-news.co.uk |date=11 February 2014 |accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, Sue Hammond announced that she would retire in the summer following 17 years as head.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Campus==\n[[Image:Map of the location of Billericay School.jpg|right|thumb|400px|The Billericay School, highlighted here by the blue dot, is situated in the south of [[Billericay]] surrounded by the A176 and B1007 roads.]]\n\nAs of May 2013 the school has A,C,D,E,F and V blocks. A B Block used to exist on the greenery, next to the car park, where the footpath now leads from the main gate to 'F' Block. B block was a two-storey wooden structure housing metal and woodworking classrooms on the ground floor and art, pottery, home economics and  technical drawing classrooms, on the first floor. It was demolished on the last day of term 1989.\n\nA Block contains mostly Maths classes and R.E classes along with humanities and Geography. This was the original building from when the school was first opened.\n\nC block is the biggest block at the school. It contains mainly Science classrooms. The main wing of the block is a 3 stories high with roughly 1 and a half of these rooms as Science labs. This block also contains the RBLC, more commonly known as the library, which houses over 30,000 books.<ref name=\"billericay1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/about_us |title=About Us / The Billericay School - A Specialist Maths & Computer School |publisher=Billericay.essex.sch.uk |date= |accessdate=13 June 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120718234923/http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/about_us |archivedate=18 July 2012  }}</ref>  It also contains (on the top floor) R.E, Media and English rooms and on the ground floor there are Drama Studios, Music rooms, Student Services and the important sick bay.\n\nD Block is the new languages block which was completed in the spring of 2013, constructed from the demountables previously used in V block. The previous D block stood on the same site, constructed from a set of demountables demolished prior to construction of the new block.\n\nE Block is a raising of the school-leaving age (Rosla) building built to house the additional students capacity needed when the school leaving age was raised to a compulsory 16.  This block contains the Art classrooms and the Food Technology and Textiles rooms and also houses Child Development.\n\nF block opened for the first time in September 1988. The original F Block contained the, then CDT Department (downstairs) and the Business Studies Department (upstairs). Later, there was a major rebuild to the front of F Block, enlarging it to take the ever-expanding school administrations. At the same time the Head Teacher's office was moved from C block (now the Withdrawal unit) to a new room in the new F Block. As ICT (IT then) expanded, the Business Studies rooms, F7 and F10 became computer rooms.  Recently F12 has been converted to house a number of PCs as has F1 with the addition of 30 PCs to augment the DT graphics lessons.\n\nIn 2004, a V block was created. It is thought that this refers to the concept of the block being a 'village' community. The V block was built to house the English department, whilst we awaited the new build block. There was a small fire in one of the old D block demountables, but the fire itself did not contribute to the installation of V block. However, 2 of the 5 buildings still remain which were not touched by the fire. V block housed the school's English department. But is now used as a cafeteria.\n\n==Sixth-form==\n[[Sixth-form]] students (years 12 and 13) have their own study areas and common room, but shares classrooms with the rest of the school.\n\n==Houses==\nSchool records show that a house system has been adopted at three periods during the school's history. During the 1930s the house names were Effingham (Red),\nRaleigh (Blue), Grenville (Green) and Drake (Yellow). From 1961 to 1968 the houses where Stock, Blunt, Norsey and Chantry. In 1969 a house system was introduced with the names of houses referencing historical figures \u2013 Fitzwalter, de Vere, Audley and Christopher Martin. The current houses are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! House Name\n! Head of House\n! Named After\n|-\n| '''Curie'''\n| Mr P Fifield<ref name=\"billericay2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/about/house-team-leaders/ |title=House Team Leaders - The Billericay School|publisher=Billericay.essex.sch.uk |date= |accessdate=11 August 2015}}</ref>\n| [[Marie Curie]]\n|-\n| '''Edison'''\n| Mr G Howells<ref name=\"billericay2\"/>\n| [[Thomas Edison]]\n|-\n| '''Keller'''\n| Miss Griffiths  <ref name=\"billericay2\"/>\n| [[Helen Keller]]\n|-\n| '''Newton'''\n| Ms J Carton <ref name=\"billericay2\"/>\n| [[Isaac Newton]]\n|-\n| '''Scott'''\n| Mr J Stokes <ref name=\"billericay2\"/>\n|[[Captain Scott]]\n|}\n\n==Visitors==\nThe sixth form was visited in May 2006 by the former MP [[Tony Benn]]<ref name=\"reports1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/oxedu_reports/display/(id)/94464|archive-url=https://archive.is/20121223164127/http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/oxedu_reports/display/(id)/94464|url-status = dead|archive-date=23 December 2012|title=Ofsted|publisher=Ofsted|date=|accessdate=13 June 2009}}</ref> who delivered a speech on politics to sixth form students. Other guests who have visited the school include survivors of the [[Auschwitz]] concentration camp [[Leon Greenman]] and [[Josef Perl]].<ref name=\"reports1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/4217361.A_message_of_hope_tied_to_Josef___s_terrible_tale/|title=Holocaust survivor Josef Perl talks to Billericay School children (From Echo)|publisher=Echo-news.co.uk |date=20 March 2009 |accessdate=15 June 2009}}</ref> Former Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher visited the school in 1980 to present then headmaster Arthur Lingard with a medal recognizing the school's achievements. However, Thatcher  had to leave early as the [[Iranian Embassy siege|SAS stormed the Iranian Embassy later the same day]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Kent |first=Sylvia |url=http://sylviakent.blogspot.co.uk/2013/09/margaret-thatcher-in-billericay.html |title=Sylvia Kent: Margaret Thatcher In Billericay School |publisher=Sylviakent.blogspot.co.uk |date=9 September 2013 |accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nAnnually [[John Baron MP]], a Conservative Party politician and MP for Billericay, comes to debate with students on political issues of a local, national and international nature.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.epolitix.com/mpwebsites/mppressreleases/mppressreleasedetails/newsarticle/john-baron-mp-visits-the-billericay-school///mpsite/john-baron/ |title=John Baron MP visits The Billericay School |publisher=ePolitix.com |date= |accessdate=13 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Notable former pupils==\n{{see also|Category:People educated at The Billericay School}}\n[[Image:Lee Evans 2004-11-13.jpg|thumb|right|100px|Comedian [[Lee Evans (comedian)|Lee Evans]] (pictured) attended the school during the mid-1970s.]]\n* [[Josh James (singer)|Josh Dubovie]], a singer who was selected to represent the UK at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2010]].<ref>{{Cite news| title =Editors picks of School Report News Day 2010 | work =BBC News School Report | publisher =BBC | date =1 April 2010 | url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/school_report/8598845.stm | accessdate =26 April 2010 }}</ref>\n* [[Lee Evans (comedian)|Lee Evans]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.getmein.com/comedy/lee-evans/info.html |title=Lee Evans Biography & Tickets @ GET ME IN! |publisher=Getmein.com|date= |accessdate=13 June 2009}}</ref> \n* British model [[David Gandy]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/1531784.0/?act=complaint&cid=408995 |title=Italian stallion? No, he's a local lad |publisher=Echo-news.co.uk |date=10 July 2007 |accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Lauren Platt]], an ''[[The X Factor (UK series 11)|X Factor]]'' finalist in [[The X Factor (UK series 11)|series 11]] of the show<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theenquirer.co.uk/lauren-platt-x-factor-dad-backs-dream/ |title=EXCLUSIVE \"She's wanted this since she was eight-years-old\" \u2013 Lauren Platt's dad backs teenager's X Factor dream &#124; The Enquirer Newspaper |publisher=Theenquirer.co.uk |date=4 September 2014 |accessdate=4 March 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Mark Sandell]], BBC producer with [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] and former husband of [[Fi Glover]] and husband of [[Victoria Derbyshire]]\n* [[Michael J. Todd|Michael Todd]] the former chief constable of Greater Manchester Police,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/mostpopular.var.2111469.mostviewed.update_tributes_to_chief_constable.phpUpdate|title=UPDATE: Tributes to Chief Constable|website=Echo}}</ref>\n* Charlie Wernham, ITV's [[Britain's Got Talent]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/2378146.billericay_schools_young_stars_shine/|title=Billericay School's young stars shine (From Echo) |publisher=Echo-news.co.uk|date=4 July 2008 |accessdate=15 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Billericay Grammar School===\n* [[Mike Edmonds]] an Ewok in ''[[Return of the Jedi]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kent |first=Sylvia |url=http://www.billericayhistory.org.uk/page_id__54_path__0p2p20p.aspx |title=Actor, Mike Edmonds' recollections &#124; A Famous Billericay Boy &#124; Schools &#124; Places |publisher=Billericay History |date=17 March 2011 |accessdate=4 March 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Ireen Sheer|Irene Wooldridge]] a participant in the Eurovision Song Contest in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1974|1974]] for Luxembourg with ''[[Bye Bye I Love You]]'' and [[Eurovision Song Contest 1978|1978]] for Germany, singing ''[[Feuer (song)|Feuer]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billericayhistory.org.uk/page/memories_of_billericay_school|title=Memories of Billericay School|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==School life and awards==\n[[File:Friends of Billericay School (emblem).gif|thumb|right|Friends Of Billericay School Logo]]\nThe school's music department has appeared on ''[[Blue Peter]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.braintreeandwithamtimes.co.uk/1998/12/18/227646.html |title=Braintree and Witham Times - Music guru is Billericay's top citizen |publisher=Archive.braintreeandwithamtimes.co.uk |date= |accessdate=15 June 2009}}</ref> and has received recognition from the [[British Naturalists\u2019 Association]] for ecological work at Mill Meadows.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basildonrecorder.co.uk/search/4058629.Nature_reserve_award_win_for_Billericay_School_pupils/ |title=Nature reserve award win for Billericay School pupils (From Basildon Recorder) |publisher=Basildonrecorder.co.uk |date=20 January 2009 |accessdate=15 June 2009}}</ref> The school is active in local public speaking competitions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basildonrecorder.co.uk/search/4068698.Mayflower_pupils_are_best_public_speakers/ |title=Mayflower pupils are best public speakers (From Basildon Recorder) |publisher=Basildonrecorder.co.uk |date=23 January 2009 |accessdate=15 June 2009}}</ref> and has organised a trip to Argentina in order to do community work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basildonrecorder.co.uk/search/3999856.Students_pack_bags_for_Argentina_trip/ |title=Students pack bags for Argentina trip (From Basildon Recorder) |publisher=Basildonrecorder.co.uk |date=24 December 2008 |accessdate=15 June 2009}}</ref> A magazine, run and published in the school library under the title of Reviewz Books, reviewed new and classic fiction and has had interviews with authors such as Stephen Fry, Sheila Norton, Iain Banks and Sharon Osbourne. The magazine was edited by Barnaby Walter (founder editor), Rebecca Bedding (deputy editor) and Frankie Burt (co-editor). It was merged in 2008 with the Speak Up website initiative which now features reviews, articles and blog posts from current and past Billericay School students. It can be found at www.billericayschool.net/speakup\n\nFOBS or ''Friends of Billericay School'' is a [[Charitable organization|charity]] which raises money for the school. Most of their income comes from various evening events, usually with singers or comedians, and the '200 Club', a monthly prize draw. The latest funding drive was used to fund the school receiving 'maths and computing college' status, and the organisation has recently raised enough funds to purchase a new school minibus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/fob/fob.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040216010523/http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/fob/fob.htm|url-status = dead|archive-date=16 February 2004|title=The Billericay School Website Friends of Billericay|date=16 February 2004|publisher=}}</ref> The schools council is called  Backchat. The house captains form a group known as Student Voice.These two groups debate with both students and the Head to work towards a better life within the school.\n\nThe school awards a number of prizes to exceptional students each year:\n\n* '''James Dorrington Award''' - The James Dorrington Award for Sport is an annual award given to a student who has excelled at sport in the past academic year. The award is named after a former student James Dorrington student who died on 1 January 2002 following the diagnosis of a brain tumour.<ref name=autogenerated1>''Images of England: The Billericay School'', by Sylvia Kent. Tempus Publications. {{ISBN|0-7524-3083-1}}. p. 123.</ref>\n* '''Jack Barren Award''' - The Jack Barren Award is given to a pupil for outstanding contribution to the life of the school. The prize was first awarded in 2000 and is named after a former govonor of the school who served for thirty-nine years.<ref name=autogenerated1b>''Images of England''. Sylvia Kent. p. 120.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Secondary schools in Essex]]\n*[[Mayflower High School]], [[Billericay]]\n*[[St John's School (Billericay)|St John's School]], [[Billericay]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Kent, S. (2003), ''Images of England: The Billericay School'', Tempus Publications\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.billericayschool.com/ Billericay School]\n* [https://twitter.com/BcaySixthForm Sixth Form Twitter]\n* [http://billericayschool.net/speakup/ Speak Up! Magazine]\n* [https://twitter.com/SpeakUp_billers Speak Up! Magazine Twitter]\n* [https://www.linkedin.com/groups/Billericay-School-Alumni-4477565 Billericay School Alumni Linkedin]\n{{Secondary schools in the Basildon district}}\n{{Schools in Essex}}\n{{Schools in England}}\n{{Schools in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Billericay}}\n{{Basildon}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Billericay School, The}}\n[[Category:Academies in Essex]]\n[[Category:Borough of Basildon]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1938]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Essex]]\n[[Category:1938 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Billericay]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name          = The Billericay School\n| image         = Billericayschoollogo.jpg\n| caption       = The school's windmill logo is based upon Billericay Post Mill, which stood on Bell Hill for 200 years before collapsing in a storm in November 1928.<ref>Kent, S. (2003), Images of England: The Billericay School , Tempus Publications, p20</ref>\n| image_size          = 100px\n| coordinates   = {{coord|51.61822|0.41967|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| motto         = Caring about success<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tes.co.uk/jobDetailsBronze_schoolInfo.aspx?ac=2749697&qry=&rslt=&cur=&UK=true |title=Employer information about The Billericay School - TES Connect |publisher=Tes.co.uk |date=14 May 2009 |accessdate=15 June 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610130704/http://www.tes.co.uk/jobDetailsBronze_schoolInfo.aspx?ac=2749697&qry=&rslt=&cur=&UK=true |archivedate=10 June 2011  }}</ref>\n| established   = 1938<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seax.essexcc.gov.uk/result_details.asp?DocID=455002 |title=Seax - Catalogue: E/E 90/7/1 Log book: Billericay Senior School Includes programme for official opening of school in May 1938 wh |publisher=Seax.essexcc.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=13 June 2009}}</ref> (predecessor institution 1878)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.schoolsnet.com/uk-schools/school-details-reviews/essex/the-billericay-school/16180339/0/195996.html |title=The Billericay School Essex: Read Parent Reviews & Rankings |publisher=Schoolsnet.com |date=17 March 2009 |accessdate=13 June 2009}}</ref>\n| type          = [[Academy (English school)|Academy]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/about_us |accessdate=18 February 2016 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120718234923/http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/about_us |archivedate=18 July 2012 }}</ref>\n|region         = Non-denominational<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tes.co.uk/jobDetailsBronze_schoolInfo.aspx?ac=2749697&qry=&rslt=&cur=&UK=true |title=Employer information about The Billericay School - TES Connect |publisher=Tes.co.uk |date=14 May 2009 |accessdate=13 June 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610130704/http://www.tes.co.uk/jobDetailsBronze_schoolInfo.aspx?ac=2749697&qry=&rslt=&cur=&UK=true |archivedate=10 June 2011  }}</ref>\n| head_label    = Headteacher\n| head          = Mr Ahson Mohammed <ref>{{cite web|title=Senior Leadership Team \u00bb Billericay School|url=http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/about/senior-leadership-team/|website=www.billericay.essex.sch.uk|accessdate=11 February 2017}}</ref>\n| chair_label   = Chair of Governors\n| chair         = Mr Colin Breathwick<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/about_us/governing_body/current_membership |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130505155925/http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/about_us/governing_body/current_membership |url-status = dead|archive-date=5 May 2013 |accessdate=11 April 2013 }}</ref>\n| specialist    =  \n| address        = School Road\n| city          = [[Billericay]]\n| county        = [[Essex]]\n| country       = England\n| postcode      = CM12 9LH\n| dfeno         = 881/5468\n| ofsted        = yes\n| urn           = 136861\n| staff         = 125 teaching,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/staff/teaching_staff |accessdate=18 February 2016 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131119212809/http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/staff/teaching_staff |archivedate=19 November 2013 }}</ref> 104 non-teaching<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/staff/support_staff |accessdate=18 February 2016 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130820000523/http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/staff/support_staff |archivedate=20 August 2013 }}</ref>\n| enrolment    = 1,715<ref>{{cite web |author=England |url=http://www.education.gov.uk/edubase/establishment/summary.xhtml?urn=136861 |title=EduBase - The Billericay School |publisher=Education.gov.uk |date=16 January 2015 |accessdate=4 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402150508/http://www.education.gov.uk/edubase/establishment/summary.xhtml?urn=136861 |archive-date=2 April 2015 |url-status = dead}}</ref>\n| gender        = Mixed<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/education/09/school_tables/secondary_schools/html/881_5468.stm | work=BBC News | title=The Billericay School | date=15 January 2009}}</ref>\n (girls:777, boys:918)<ref name=\"gazette-news\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gazette-news.co.uk/li/secondary_schools.detail.VGhlIEJpbGxlcmljYXkgU2Nob29sAENNMTIgOUxI/ |publisher=Gazette-news.co.uk |date= |accessdate=17 May 2014 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924021124/http://www.gazette-news.co.uk/li/secondary_schools.detail.VGhlIEJpbGxlcmljYXkgU2Nob29sAENNMTIgOUxI/ |archivedate=24 September 2015  }}</ref>\n| lower_age     = 11<ref name=\"download1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/oxedu_reports/download/(id)/94464/(as)/115384_311932.pdf |title=Find an inspection report |publisher=Ofsted |date= |accessdate=17 May 2014 }}{{Dead link|date=June 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref>\n| upper_age     = 18<ref name=\"download1\"/>\n| houses        = Scott, Keller, Edison, Curie and Newton.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/content/download/186/696/file/Prospectuscover.pdf |accessdate=12 June 2009 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n| colours       = Black and gold {{color box|Black}}{{color box|Gold}}\n| website       = http://www.billericayschool.com/\n}}\n\n'''The Billericay School'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/ |title=Home / The Billericay School - A Specialist Maths & Computer School |publisher=Billericay.essex.sch.uk |date= |accessdate=15 June 2009}}</ref> is an [[Academy (English school)|academy secondary school]] and [[sixth form]] college<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/sixth_form |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090727133819/http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/sixth_form |url-status = dead|archive-date=27 July 2009 |title=Sixth Form / The Billericay School - A Specialist Maths & Computer School |publisher=Billericay.essex.sch.uk |date= |accessdate=15 June 2009 }}</ref> located in [[Billericay]], England.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/contact_us |title=Contact Us / The Billericay School - A Specialist Maths & Computer School |publisher=Billericay.essex.sch.uk |date= |accessdate=15 June 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090728033641/http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/contact_us |archivedate=28 July 2009  }}</ref> The school is led by headmaster Ahson Mohammed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/about_us/headteacher |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712035122/http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/about_us/headteacher |url-status = dead|archive-date=12 July 2011 |title=Headteacher / About Us / The Billericay School - A Specialist Maths & Computer School |publisher=Billericay.essex.sch.uk |date= |accessdate=15 June 2009 }}</ref> and has an enrollment of 1695. As part of the [[Billericay Education Consortium]]  the school forms part of a grouping considered to provide the best teacher training in the country according to the ''Good Teacher Training Guide''.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-14486989 | work=BBC News | title=Billericay Consortium 'top' for teacher training | date=11 August 2011}}</ref> According to [[Ofsted]] the school is \"an over-subscribed Mathematics and Computing specialist school mainly serving the town of [[Billericay]] but also drawing students from [[Basildon]] and nearby areas\".<ref>Ofsted, The Billericay School, Inspection Report, 5 March 2008, p3.</ref> In its most recent Ofsted inspection in 2013, the school was graded as 'good'.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Ofsted {{!}} The Billericay School|url = http://reports.ofsted.gov.uk/inspection-reports/find-inspection-report/provider/ELS/136861|website = reports.ofsted.gov.uk|accessdate = 11 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Admissions==\nAs a comprehensive school admission is primarily dictated by residing in/proximity to the catchment area as well as the presence of siblings at the school. However, the school is able to operate some academic selection and 10% of applicants are chosen based on aptitude in ICT which is one of the school's specialisms.\n\nThe 2013 admissions document lists a number of criteria to determine priority in the event of over-subscription for places:\n*Relevant looked-after children as defined in Section 22 of the Children Act 1989\n*Children residing in the school\u2019s defined catchment area\n*Children with a sibling attending the school\n*Medical grounds, supported by a doctor\u2019s certificate.\n*Distance from the home to school (based on straight line measurement) with those living nearer being accorded the higher priority.\n\nFurther information relating to admissions can be found on the school's website.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/parents/admissions |accessdate=18 February 2016 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229133059/http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/parents/admissions |archivedate=29 February 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Academic reputation==\nThe 2012 Governor's report lists a number of academic achievements at [[GCSE]] and [[GCE Advanced Level|A-level]].<ref name=\"aboutus\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/about_us/governing_body/governing_body_reports |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130505154056/http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/about_us/governing_body/governing_body_reports |url-status = dead|archive-date=5 May 2013 |accessdate=28 April 2013 }}</ref>\n\n*84% of GCSE students at the school gained 5 A*-C grades in any subjects.<ref name=\"aboutus\" />\n*100% of GCSE  students gained a A*-C grade pass in ICT<ref name=\"aboutus\" />\n*78% of GCSE  students gained a A*-C grade pass in Mathematics<ref name=\"aboutus\" />\n*78* of GCSE  students gained at least 2 A*-C grade passes in Science<ref name=\"aboutus\" />\n*The mean average points total for a GCSE student was 452 which is equivalent to 10 GCSEs at grade 'B'.<ref name=\"aboutus\" />\n*At A-level the mean points total per student was 874.2 which is approximately equivalent to ABBb<ref name=\"aboutus\" />\n*47.2% of grades at A-level were either 'A' or 'B'<ref name=\"aboutus\" />\n*25 A* grades were achieved at A-level<ref name=\"aboutus\" />\n\n{| style=\"margin:1em auto 1em auto; width:40%;\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! '''League Table Measure''' !! '''2012'''  !! '''2013'''\n|-\n| 5 A*-C (inc English and Maths) || 57%<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.education.gov.uk/cgi-bin/schools/performance/school.pl?urn=136861 |title=The Department for Education - Performance Tables - School Details |publisher=Education.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref> ||73%<ref name=\"telegraph1\">{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/leaguetables/10590631/GCSE-school-league-tables-2014-compare-your-schools-performance.html#area/Essex/136861 | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first1=Joel | last1=Gunter | first2=Graeme | last2=Paton | first3=Dan | last3=Palmer | first4=Siva | last4=Bonagiri | first5=Mark | last5=Oliver | title=GCSE school league tables 2014: compare your school's performance | date=23 January 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| English Bacc %<ref>The percentage of students gaining 5 A*-C grades in Maths, English, two science subjects, a language and either history or geography</ref> || 6%<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/special/education/school_tables/secondary/12/html/va_881.stm?compare= | work=BBC News | title=Secondary school league tables in Essex | date=23 April 2013}}</ref> ||25%<ref name=\"telegraph1\"/>\n|-\n| Value Added<ref>A  measure of how well pupils are helped to progress from their starting point. A score above 1,000 is better than the national average</ref> || 996.5<ref name=\"bbc\" /> || \n|-\n| Average A/AS- level points || 874.7<ref name=\"bbc\" /> || \n|}\n\n2009/10 leavers data showed that 73% of A-level leavers go onto another educational destination, 70 students went on to higher education and  9 of these students went on to [[Russell Group]] universities.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/interactive/2012/jul/18/oxbridge-students-secondary-school | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Simon | last=Rogers | title=Higher education destination by school: find out how many students from your school go to Oxbridge and top universities? | date=18 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Head teachers==\n{| style=\"margin:1em auto 1em auto; width:40%;\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Head Teacher\n|-\n|1938\u20131949 ||Percy George White\n|-\n|1949\u20131955 ||Ronald Eden\n|-\n|1955\u20131968 ||John Goldwin\n|-\n|1968\u20131991 ||Arthur Lingard\n|-\n|1991\u20131998||Robert Goodier\n|-\n|1998<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = Long-serving Billericay headteacher to retire after 17 years at school|url = http://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/11831870.Long_serving_Billericay_headteacher_to_retire_after_17_years_at_school/?ref=mr|website = Echo|accessdate = 12 August 2015}}</ref>\u20132015<ref name=\":0\" />||Sue Hammond\n|-\n|2015\u2013Present||Ahxx Mohammed<ref>http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/assets/Uploads/Parents/Newsletters/Newsletter-Summer-July-2015.pdf</ref>\n|}\n\n==History==\nThe school was formally opened in 1938 by admiral Sir Vernon Haggard using a ceremonial silver key handed to him by the first headmaster P.G. White. However, a predecessor institution called Great Burstead Board School opened on 13 February  1878. This school was situated just across from Laindon Road and P.G. White who was Billericay School's first headmaster was appointed head of the senior mixed department here in 1923. The Billericay School was built as by the 1930s the school was struggling to cope with a growing enrollment and plans were drawn up for a new school big enough to cater for Billericay\u2019s growing population.\n\nCosting \u00a322,400 Billericay School opened its doors in 1937 a year before its 'official' opening as a [[grammar school]]. Air raid shelters were built almost immediately  to protect students from Luftwaffe planes travelling to London on bombing raids during World War II. The school was built upon the site of an Iron Age foundry where prior to the building of the school a cornfield and a farm was located.\n\nP.G. White served a headmaster until 1949 when he died suddenly on holiday shortly before he was due to retire. Arthur Lingard became headmaster in 1949 and oversaw the school's transformation to a comprehensive on 1 September 1968 and the building of the school\u2019s sixth form centre which occurred in the 1960s. During the 1970s exchanges began with international schools including an annual trip to the Einstein Gymnasium in [[Reutlingen]] in Germany - an exchange programme that continues to this day.  The Parents\u2019 Guild (later Friends of Billericay School) was also formed in this decade. Robert Goodier became headmaster in 1991 and oversaw the move away from LEA governance to self-governance.\n\nThe school's Music Studio was finished in 1991 and the decade saw a period of success for the Music Department under the headship of Mr John Stevenson including appearances at the London TV Arts Festival and on the BBC's Blue Peter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCvWxoBF-FHkUQ06lWN0ImLg?feature=watch |title=John Stevenson |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref> In 1997 the school was awarded its third Schools Curriculum Award by Princess Anne. Sue Hammond became the first female head of the school in Easter 1998 and in 1999 the [[Resource-based learning|Resource Based Learning Centre]] (RBLC) was opened. In March 2002 the school was the subject of a channel 5 documentary concerning a school reunion for pupils who attended the school between 1980 and 1982.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9Y-vAFei0og |title=Billericay School Reunion - March 2002 |publisher=YouTube |date=26 August 2012 |accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Billericayschool.jpg|thumb|right|300px|A-block can be seen in the background of the front cover of Sylvia Kent's book on The Billericay School.]]\n\nThe School achieved [[Mathematics and Computing College|Maths and Computing College]] status in 2003 allowing some use of selection based on aptitude in these subjects. It was thought that this status would generate an additional \u00a31 million worth of funding, but a [[government]] policy on foundation schools reduced this sum significantly. The school has since converted to academy status, but continues to have Maths and Computing as a specialism.\n\nThe 2000s saw long-running attempts to sell disused land adjacent to the school in order to fund a series of improvements\nDevelopment was initially refused<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basildonrecorder.co.uk/search/2072077.Billericay_School_plan_set_for_refusal/ |title=Billericay School plan set for refusal (From Basildon Recorder) |publisher=Basildonrecorder.co.uk |date=26 February 2008 |accessdate=15 June 2009}}</ref> but was appealed.<ref name=\"billericay3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/local_news/billericay/3982265.Planning_inquiry_told_green_belt_land_sale_vital_for_Billericay_School/ |title=Planning inquiry told green belt land sale vital for Billericay School (From Echo) |publisher=Echo-news.co.uk |date=17 December 2008 |accessdate=15 June 2009}}</ref> In 2009 approval was gained to develop 51 new homes upon a six-acre plot.<ref name=\"billericay3\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/local_news/billericay/4079551.Green_belt_homes_fury/ |title=Green belt homes fury (From Echo) |publisher=Echo-news.co.uk |date=28 January 2009 |accessdate=12 June 2009}}</ref><ref>http://www.investmentland.com/news.php</ref>\n\nChanges were made in the 2005/06 academic year which cut the lunch break from 1 hour to 45 mins so that the school day finished at 3.00pm rather than 3.15pm. In January 2007 the school was at scene of a [[BBC London]] news report after a gas explosion scare in nearby South Green, down Southend Road. The school was used to house those evacuated from the surrounding area. No explosion from the acetylene and oxygen cylinders occurred but one man suffered burns from the fire. The scare scene was 3 houses away from the South Green Memorial Hall.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/essex/6299355.stm | work=BBC News | title=Explosion fear prompts evacuation | date=25 January 2007 | accessdate=25 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 it was proposed that the a Billericay Community Trust be formed in order to increase standards at the school.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basildonrecorder.co.uk/search/1407975.Schools_welcome_the_chance_to_cut_loose/ |title=Schools welcome the chance to cut loose (From Basildon Recorder) |publisher=Basildonrecorder.co.uk |date=19 May 2007 |accessdate=15 June 2009}}</ref> This would involve a partnership with the multinational technology corporation [[Dell]], something that the Essex branch of the [[National Union of Teachers]] has objected to.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/content/download/623/2660/version/1/file/Billericay+Community+Trust+Statutory+Proposals.pdf |accessdate=18 February 2016 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120217065424/http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/content/download/623/2660/version/1/file/Billericay+Community+Trust+Statutory+Proposals.pdf |archivedate=17 February 2012 }}</ref>\nIn 2010 The School suffered from austerity measure budget cuts and was one of several schools in Essex which lost out on money promised under the [[Building Schools for the Future]] programme.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/8259630.Government_pulls_plug_on_project_to_refurbish_seven_south_Essex_schools/ |title=Government pulls plug on project to refurbish seven south Essex schools |publisher=Echo-news.co.uk |date=8 July 2010 |accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref>\n[[Image:Menenpoort ieper.jpg|thumb|left|The school stage an annual trip for GCSE History students to the see World War I battlefields in Belgium taking in sites including the [[Menin Gate]] (pictured).]]\n\nIn 2011 the school received media attention when a local newspaper called the [[Billericay Gazette]] printed indiscreet [[Twitter]] comments made by Charlotte Berry who was a Deputy Headteacher at the school. Responding to the incident headmistress Sue Hammond stated: \"The member of staff\u2019s Twitter account appears to have been individually targeted, accessing conversations with friends unconnected with the school and taken completely out of context. The school is saddened that the decision has been taken to print these individual unrelated comments, however indiscreet, in a newspaper medium to an audience for whom they were not intended\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2051255/Billericay-assistant-head-Charlotte-Berry-investigated-expletive-filled-Twitter-posts.html | location=London | work=Daily Mail | first=Emily | last=Allen | title='I'm a lazy slut and I swear a lot': Essex assistant headteacher, 42, sparks investigation for her 'talk to teens' Twitter posts | date=20 October 2011}}</ref> There was further controversy that year when the school's sixth-form prom ended after some students were allegedly found taking drugs.<ref>{{cite web |last=Gazette |first=Billericay |url=http://www.thisistotalessex.co.uk/Prom-night-ended-drugs/story-13026028-detail/story.html |title=Prom night ended after drugs found |publisher=Thisistotalessex.co.uk |date=30 July 2011 |accessdate=17 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131107034532/http://www.thisistotalessex.co.uk/Prom-night-ended-drugs/story-13026028-detail/story.html |archive-date=7 November 2013 |url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nThe school converted to academy status on 1 July 2011.<ref name=\"aboutus\" /> Becoming an academy school gives the school greater budgetary autonomy and control over its curriculum.In 2013 the school received national media attention after banning male students from having [[pompadour (hairstyle)|pompadour]] style haircuts. The measure was criticized as draconian by some parents. One parent told the Daily Mail newspaper: \"I can understand banning some extreme haircuts but this is just ridiculous. This haircut has been about since the 50s and it didn't even shock people then\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2333446/Essex-school-warns-pupils-banned-classroom-copying-TOWIE-haircuts.html | location=London | work=Daily Mail | title=Essex school warns pupils they will be banned from the classroom for copying TOWIE haircuts | first=Tara | last=Brady | date=30 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 the school announced a partnership to aid [[The Deanes School]] in Benfleet which has been threatened with closure due to falling student numbers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/11000275.Joining_with_Deanes_will_make_us_both_stronger/ |title=Joining with Deanes will make us both stronger |publisher=Echo-news.co.uk |date=11 February 2014 |accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, Sue Hammond announced that she would retire in the summer following 17 years as head.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Campus==\n[[Image:Map of the location of Billericay School.jpg|right|thumb|400px|The Billericay School, highlighted here by the blue dot, is situated in the south of [[Billericay]] surrounded by the A176 and B1007 roads.]]\n\nAs of May 2013 the school has A,C,D,E,F and V blocks. A B Block used to exist on the greenery, next to the car park, where the footpath now leads from the main gate to 'F' Block. B block was a two-storey wooden structure housing metal and woodworking classrooms on the ground floor and art, pottery, home economics and  technical drawing classrooms, on the first floor. It was demolished on the last day of term 1989.\n\nA Block contains mostly Maths classes and R.E classes along with humanities and Geography. This was the original building from when the school was first opened.\n\nC block is the biggest block at the school. It contains mainly Science classrooms. The main wing of the block is a 3 stories high with roughly 1 and a half of these rooms as Science labs. This block also contains the RBLC, more commonly known as the library, which houses over 30,000 books.<ref name=\"billericay1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/about_us |title=About Us / The Billericay School - A Specialist Maths & Computer School |publisher=Billericay.essex.sch.uk |date= |accessdate=13 June 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120718234923/http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/bl/about_us |archivedate=18 July 2012  }}</ref>  It also contains (on the top floor) R.E, Media and English rooms and on the ground floor there are Drama Studios, Music rooms, Student Services and the important sick bay.\n\nD Block is the new languages block which was completed in the spring of 2013, constructed from the demountables previously used in V block. The previous D block stood on the same site, constructed from a set of demountables demolished prior to construction of the new block.\n\nE Block is a raising of the school-leaving age (Rosla) building built to house the additional students capacity needed when the school leaving age was raised to a compulsory 16.  This block contains the Art classrooms and the Food Technology and Textiles rooms and also houses Child Development.\n\nF block opened for the first time in September 1988. The original F Block contained the, then CDT Department (downstairs) and the Business Studies Department (upstairs). Later, there was a major rebuild to the front of F Block, enlarging it to take the ever-expanding school administrations. At the same time the Head Teacher's office was moved from C block (now the Withdrawal unit) to a new room in the new F Block. As ICT (IT then) expanded, the Business Studies rooms, F7 and F10 became computer rooms.  Recently F12 has been converted to house a number of PCs as has F1 with the addition of 30 PCs to augment the DT graphics lessons.\n\nIn 2004, a V block was created. It is thought that this refers to the concept of the block being a 'village' community. The V block was built to house the English department, whilst we awaited the new build block. There was a small fire in one of the old D block demountables, but the fire itself did not contribute to the installation of V block. However, 2 of the 5 buildings still remain which were not touched by the fire. V block housed the school's English department. But is now used as a cafeteria.\n\n==Sixth-form==\n[[Sixth-form]] students (years 12 and 13) have their own study areas and common room, but shares classrooms with the rest of the school.\n\n==Houses==\nSchool records show that a house system has been adopted at three periods during the school's history. During the 1930s the house names were Effingham (Red),\nRaleigh (Blue), Grenville (Green) and Drake (Yellow). From 1961 to 1968 the houses where Stock, Blunt, Norsey and Chantry. In 1969 a house system was introduced with the names of houses referencing historical figures \u2013 Fitzwalter, de Vere, Audley and Christopher Martin. The current houses are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! House Name\n! Head of House\n! Named After\n|-\n| '''Curie'''\n| Mr P Fifield<ref name=\"billericay2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/about/house-team-leaders/ |title=House Team Leaders - The Billericay School|publisher=Billericay.essex.sch.uk |date= |accessdate=11 August 2015}}</ref>\n| [[Marie Curie]]\n|-\n| '''Edison'''\n| Mr G Howells<ref name=\"billericay2\"/>\n| [[Thomas Edison]]\n|-\n| '''Keller'''\n| Miss Griffiths  <ref name=\"billericay2\"/>\n| [[Helen Keller]]\n|-\n| '''Newton'''\n| Ms J Carton <ref name=\"billericay2\"/>\n| [[Isaac Newton]]\n|-\n| '''Scott'''\n| Mr J Stokes <ref name=\"billericay2\"/>\n|[[Captain Scott]]\n|}\n\n==Visitors==\nThe sixth form was visited in May 2006 by the former MP [[Tony Benn]]<ref name=\"reports1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/oxedu_reports/display/(id)/94464|archive-url=https://archive.is/20121223164127/http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/oxedu_reports/display/(id)/94464|url-status = dead|archive-date=23 December 2012|title=Ofsted|publisher=Ofsted|date=|accessdate=13 June 2009}}</ref> who delivered a speech on politics to sixth form students. Other guests who have visited the school include survivors of the [[Auschwitz]] concentration camp [[Leon Greenman]] and [[Josef Perl]].<ref name=\"reports1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/4217361.A_message_of_hope_tied_to_Josef___s_terrible_tale/|title=Holocaust survivor Josef Perl talks to Billericay School children (From Echo)|publisher=Echo-news.co.uk |date=20 March 2009 |accessdate=15 June 2009}}</ref> Former Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher visited the school in 1980 to present then headmaster Arthur Lingard with a medal recognizing the school's achievements. However, Thatcher  had to leave early as the [[Iranian Embassy siege|SAS stormed the Iranian Embassy later the same day]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Kent |first=Sylvia |url=http://sylviakent.blogspot.co.uk/2013/09/margaret-thatcher-in-billericay.html |title=Sylvia Kent: Margaret Thatcher In Billericay School |publisher=Sylviakent.blogspot.co.uk |date=9 September 2013 |accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nAnnually [[John Baron MP]], a Conservative Party politician and MP for Billericay, comes to debate with students on political issues of a local, national and international nature.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.epolitix.com/mpwebsites/mppressreleases/mppressreleasedetails/newsarticle/john-baron-mp-visits-the-billericay-school///mpsite/john-baron/ |title=John Baron MP visits The Billericay School |publisher=ePolitix.com |date= |accessdate=13 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Notable former pupils==\n{{see also|Category:People educated at The Billericay School}}\n[[Image:Lee Evans 2004-11-13.jpg|thumb|right|100px|Comedian [[Lee Evans (comedian)|Lee Evans]] (pictured) attended the school during the mid-1970s.]]\n* [[Josh James (singer)|Josh Dubovie]], a singer who was selected to represent the UK at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2010]].<ref>{{Cite news| title =Editors picks of School Report News Day 2010 | work =BBC News School Report | publisher =BBC | date =1 April 2010 | url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/school_report/8598845.stm | accessdate =26 April 2010 }}</ref>\n* [[Lee Evans (comedian)|Lee Evans]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.getmein.com/comedy/lee-evans/info.html |title=Lee Evans Biography & Tickets @ GET ME IN! |publisher=Getmein.com|date= |accessdate=13 June 2009}}</ref> \n* British model [[David Gandy]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/1531784.0/?act=complaint&cid=408995 |title=Italian stallion? No, he's a local lad |publisher=Echo-news.co.uk |date=10 July 2007 |accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Lauren Platt]], an ''[[The X Factor (UK series 11)|X Factor]]'' finalist in [[The X Factor (UK series 11)|series 11]] of the show<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theenquirer.co.uk/lauren-platt-x-factor-dad-backs-dream/ |title=EXCLUSIVE \"She's wanted this since she was eight-years-old\" \u2013 Lauren Platt's dad backs teenager's X Factor dream &#124; The Enquirer Newspaper |publisher=Theenquirer.co.uk |date=4 September 2014 |accessdate=4 March 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Mark Sandell]], BBC producer with [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] and former husband of [[Fi Glover]] and husband of [[Victoria Derbyshire]]\n* [[Michael J. Todd|Michael Todd]] the former chief constable of Greater Manchester Police,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/mostpopular.var.2111469.mostviewed.update_tributes_to_chief_constable.phpUpdate|title=UPDATE: Tributes to Chief Constable|website=Echo}}</ref>\n* Charlie Wernham, ITV's [[Britain's Got Talent]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/2378146.billericay_schools_young_stars_shine/|title=Billericay School's young stars shine (From Echo) |publisher=Echo-news.co.uk|date=4 July 2008 |accessdate=15 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Billericay Grammar School===\n* [[Mike Edmonds]] an Ewok in ''[[Return of the Jedi]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kent |first=Sylvia |url=http://www.billericayhistory.org.uk/page_id__54_path__0p2p20p.aspx |title=Actor, Mike Edmonds' recollections &#124; A Famous Billericay Boy &#124; Schools &#124; Places |publisher=Billericay History |date=17 March 2011 |accessdate=4 March 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Ireen Sheer|Irene Wooldridge]] a participant in the Eurovision Song Contest in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1974|1974]] for Luxembourg with ''[[Bye Bye I Love You]]'' and [[Eurovision Song Contest 1978|1978]] for Germany, singing ''[[Feuer (song)|Feuer]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billericayhistory.org.uk/page/memories_of_billericay_school|title=Memories of Billericay School|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==School life and awards==\n[[File:Friends of Billericay School (emblem).gif|thumb|right|Friends Of Billericay School Logo]]\nThe school's music department has appeared on ''[[Blue Peter]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.braintreeandwithamtimes.co.uk/1998/12/18/227646.html |title=Braintree and Witham Times - Music guru is Billericay's top citizen |publisher=Archive.braintreeandwithamtimes.co.uk |date= |accessdate=15 June 2009}}</ref> and has received recognition from the [[British Naturalists\u2019 Association]] for ecological work at Mill Meadows.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basildonrecorder.co.uk/search/4058629.Nature_reserve_award_win_for_Billericay_School_pupils/ |title=Nature reserve award win for Billericay School pupils (From Basildon Recorder) |publisher=Basildonrecorder.co.uk |date=20 January 2009 |accessdate=15 June 2009}}</ref> The school is active in local public speaking competitions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basildonrecorder.co.uk/search/4068698.Mayflower_pupils_are_best_public_speakers/ |title=Mayflower pupils are best public speakers (From Basildon Recorder) |publisher=Basildonrecorder.co.uk |date=23 January 2009 |accessdate=15 June 2009}}</ref> and has organised a trip to Argentina in order to do community work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basildonrecorder.co.uk/search/3999856.Students_pack_bags_for_Argentina_trip/ |title=Students pack bags for Argentina trip (From Basildon Recorder) |publisher=Basildonrecorder.co.uk |date=24 December 2008 |accessdate=15 June 2009}}</ref> A magazine, run and published in the school library under the title of Reviewz Books, reviewed new and classic fiction and has had interviews with authors such as Stephen Fry, Sheila Norton, Iain Banks and Sharon Osbourne. The magazine was edited by Barnaby Walter (founder editor), Rebecca Bedding (deputy editor) and Frankie Burt (co-editor). It was merged in 2008 with the Speak Up website initiative which now features reviews, articles and blog posts from current and past Billericay School students. It can be found at www.billericayschool.net/speakup\n\nFOBS or ''Friends of Billericay School'' is a [[Charitable organization|charity]] which raises money for the school. Most of their income comes from various evening events, usually with singers or comedians, and the '200 Club', a monthly prize draw. The latest funding drive was used to fund the school receiving 'maths and computing college' status, and the organisation has recently raised enough funds to purchase a new school minibus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/fob/fob.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040216010523/http://www.billericay.essex.sch.uk/fob/fob.htm|url-status = dead|archive-date=16 February 2004|title=The Billericay School Website Friends of Billericay|date=16 February 2004|publisher=}}</ref> The schools council is called  Backchat. The house captains form a group known as Student Voice.These two groups debate with both students and the Head to work towards a better life within the school.\n\nThe school awards a number of prizes to exceptional students each year:\n\n* '''James Dorrington Award''' - The James Dorrington Award for Sport is an annual award given to a student who has excelled at sport in the past academic year. The award is named after a former student James Dorrington student who died on 1 January 2002 following the diagnosis of a brain tumour.<ref name=autogenerated1>''Images of England: The Billericay School'', by Sylvia Kent. Tempus Publications. {{ISBN|0-7524-3083-1}}. p. 123.</ref>\n* '''Jack Barren Award''' - The Jack Barren Award is given to a pupil for outstanding contribution to the life of the school. The prize was first awarded in 2000 and is named after a former govonor of the school who served for thirty-nine years.<ref name=autogenerated1b>''Images of England''. Sylvia Kent. p. 120.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Secondary schools in Essex]]\n*[[Mayflower High School]], [[Billericay]]\n*[[St John's School (Billericay)|St John's School]], [[Billericay]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Kent, S. (2003), ''Images of England: The Billericay School'', Tempus Publications\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.billericayschool.com/ Billericay School]\n* [https://twitter.com/BcaySixthForm Sixth Form Twitter]\n* [http://billericayschool.net/speakup/ Speak Up! Magazine]\n* [https://twitter.com/SpeakUp_billers Speak Up! Magazine Twitter]\n* [https://www.linkedin.com/groups/Billericay-School-Alumni-4477565 Billericay School Alumni Linkedin]\n{{Secondary schools in the Basildon district}}\n{{Schools in Essex}}\n{{Schools in England}}\n{{Schools in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Billericay}}\n{{Basildon}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Billericay School, The}}\n[[Category:Academies in Essex]]\n[[Category:Borough of Basildon]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1938]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Essex]]\n[[Category:1938 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Billericay]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c5:d105:f800:1c56:e74a:84a8:38bd", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Billericay_School"}
